textRun.content: Hi! It’s Arglin. You’ll probably see me around here quite a lot for the next few months (or honestly, probably always, because I keep on finding more linkages to document).

This place is still pretty rough around the edges because this has been an ongoing project since February of 2021. There’s going to be a lot of changes being made between some diagrams so if some descriptions seemingly cut off arbitrarily, then it’s probably because I’m busy updating other sections in the meanwhile.
FOR THOSE WHO ARE ACCESSING THIS DOCUMENT VIA A THIRD PARTY READING, PLEASE REFER TO HERE:
Alternatively, you can find the document via the Poly Bridge Discord Server, or through my YouTube channel:
The main reason for this is that third party sources may have broken formatting and nonfunctional hyperlinks.

2022-09-08: Some recent news!! In hopes of making it easier for people to find or reference linkages, I am working on transferring the repository to a website hosted by Miraheze!
, but you can check it out here anyways.
If you would like to help out, feel free to DM me on Discord!

I would like to thank Cookiebox678 and Chakot (Vaigg) for avidly partaking in this expedition through the discovery and development of mechanical linkages in Poly Bridge 2. They have both done a ton to help drive my interest in mechanical work.
Some additional thanks to the following folks:
Mrallenengasser - Major developments in several mechanisms, a lot of mathematics and programming, and creating some of the diagrams in this document.
CursorCoercer - A lot of mathematics and solving logistics.
Aristides Gogoussis - Development of lemniscate mechanisms, along with extensive discussions with me on linkages.
Palfly Kampling - Assistance in modeling linkages in GeoGebra, development in mimicking prismatic joint behavior and reverser linkages.
Luna Kampling - Assistance in calculating inversor cell mechanics and Roberts linkage behavior.
FestiveBook - Providing the generalization of double kite linkages.
Lazy Comet - Development in on-grid angle converters.
Shmojelfed - Development in on-grid angle converters.
Squash - Development in on-grid angle converters.
Akagami Hero - Development and co-development of several heart mechanisms... (...これは長い話なので、あまり深く考えないでください。)
Scurfle(madur) - Co-development of the new contraparallelogram bracing.
Sharle Quint (Sharlequin) - Prototyping/cross-checking the contraparallelogram bracing in real life to prove its viability.

I would like to also extend my gratitude to MoonlitJolty, Conqu3red, Tran Fox, Bram2323, and many of the other members of the Poly Bridge 2 Polytech team, for making all of the visual enhancement mods used in this repository, along with Nguyen Duc Thang (thang010146) and 上木 敬士郎 (Ueki Keishiro), both for providing and maintaining extensive databases of animations for many linkages, and Mr. Thang for directly keeping in contact with me to assist in any inquiries and optimizations.

This variation of bracing I discovered requires more links in real life application. However in Poly Bridge, it is significantly more versatile, and is capable of covering all known contraparallelograms including ones that the conventional bracing method isn’t capable of doing without split joints and muscles to create overlapping links.
The following demonstrates how to construct this. Blue links are new links being constructed per step, and the rightmost diagram shows two examples.
2. Bisect either opposing links of the contraparallelogram and draw a line connecting their centers together.
3. Create a line that goes through the center of either of the bisected links that is perpendicular of step 2’s line.
4. Paste the opposing beam anywhere along step 3’s line such that the line passes through the center.
5. Remove the construction lines and revert the bisected links back to being normal.
6. Add four new beams to form a new contraparallelogram and parallelogram.

Rather than using the grid that comes with the game, an isometric grid is based on constructing equilateral triangles.
It’s often recommended to first lay out the desired link length prior to constructing the linkage. This allows you to copy and paste without requiring having to rotate the links 60 or 120 degrees.

To bisect a short distance between two points, connect the two points with the trace tool and set it to a straight line. Fiddle with the Max Length fill slider until you get an even number of links between the two points. The center joints will be the point of bisection.

To bisect a distance between two points that is shorter than 1 meter, place two equally sized bars of any reasonable length, preferably small, in opposing directions. Connect the joints of the two new bars with a trace tool, set to a straight line. Fiddle with the Max Length fill slider until you get an even number of bars between the two points. The center joint will be the point of bisection.

To bisect an extremely large distance, you can use the first method, however this method can help speed up the efficiency of finding the center more easily without as much fiddling needed with the Max Length fill slider. (The larger the distance, the more sensitive it is to fiddle with and the more random it is to get an even number of links)

Connect the points with a trace tool, and adjust it to be somewhat shallow, but still fairly to find the vertex of the trace . Copy the whole curve, then flip both vertically and horizontally before pasting. Find the closest points of the vertex, and connect them together with the trace tool, and use Method 1. The center joint will be the point of bisection.

Kempe Kite Linkages rely on having a deltoid being nested within another deltoid of the same proportions.
The FestiveBook Generalization is constructed like this:
Copy a base link and rotate it to some arbitrary angle.
Using copying, flipping, and pasting, generating any number of rhombuses shown in pink as desired. (Below shows the construction of just two as an example.)
Complete the deltoid and remove residual pink scaffold.
Repeat Steps 2 and 3with the two blue links.
Combine the two deltoids together to form the nested deltoid pair.
FestiveBook’s generalization can be improved to allow us to generate on-grid nested deltoids more easily.
First off, rather than primarily relying on rhombuses to locate the final point on a deltoid, an angle bisector can be used to solve for the new point.

To construct the angle bisector, create a rhombus by copying then flipping the original two links in both axes. From there, connect the new diagonal formed by the rhombus. Copy the diagonal and extend it as far as required. Merge the new extension into a single line and remove the construction lines.

From here any point that lands on the angle bisector will generate a deltoid, and the angle bisector is guaranteed to hit an infinite number of points on the grid if it is generated from two links that are also on-grid.
Once a deltoid is chosen, you can flip one of the longer links. Then to complete the new deltoid, draw the angle bisector of the mechanism and find where it intersects with the ground link.
There are three special types of grid constructible deltoids that have a ground link that is flat, which allows for this new generalization to apply effectively:
Type I (top diagram) uses a deltoid arranged in a fashion such that the shorter links (shown in black) are rotated 90 degrees of each other.
Type II (middle diagram) uses any deltoid arranged in a fashion such that the shorter links are the hypotenuse of a
Type III (bottom diagram) uses a deltoid arranged in a fashion such that the shorter links are collinear, creating an isosceles triangle.
From here, the FestiveBook-Kampling generalization can be applied to all three types of deltoids.

Angle Bisector - A Generalization on all Angle Reversers and Doublers
Every 1:1 Reverser has the following three components.
At this level of complexity, it is more appropriate for us to rename these to the following:
Defining any two angles will define the third angle.
In a generalized form, Angle B is always the angle bisector of Angles A and C.
We can check this by using the mechanisms that we already know: 1:1 Reversers and 1:2 Converters.
In a 1:1 Reverser, we set Angle B (Chassis) to equal 0°.
This states that if we let A be the input, this will yield an angle for C that is the opposite of angle A, and vice versa.
In a 1:2 Converter, we set Angle A (Input Crank) to equal 0°.
This states that if we let B be the input, this will yield an angle for C that is double angle B.
Angle bisectors will be crucial in understanding why the following mechanisms work.
Notation will be shown in [A, B, C].
An idea first proposed by Chakot and later generalized by CursorCoercer, the method explains how you can get any arbitrary integer revolutions “N” out of one revolution in the shortest chain of
If the Value of N is even, divide by 2.
If the Value of N is odd, add 1, then divide by 2.
Repeat the process until N becomes 1.
E.g. Output makes 19 rotation per single rotation of the input.
We will now use the instructions we have derived to create the chain of Angle Bisectors that will get our desired value.
For every notation, create a new Angle Bisector linkage.
[0, 1, 2] - Angle Doubler (This is what the notation for an Angle Doubler is.)
[1, 2, 3] - Connect A to the beginning input, and B to the previous Angle Bisector’s output.
[1, 3, 5] - Connect A to the beginning input, and B to the previous Angle Bisector’s output.
[0, 5, 10] - Anchor A in place, and B to the previous Angle Bisector’s output.
[1, 10, 19] - Connect A to the beginning input, and B to the previous Angle Bisector’s output.

Advanced Engines (sometimes Engines are also called Motors) are mechanisms that are a method to power mechanisms. The simplest is the mechanisms which perform a
input, addressed near the beginning of the repository. Below are more sophisticated forms of powering such mechanisms.

Complex Hydraulic Engines are hydraulic engines that are often more complicated than needed. Most rarely serve any purpose, and are often just to make a mechanical bridge prettier or just to flex. However, some can be proven useful under specific circumstances.
Hydraulic Engines with a Single Axis of Symmetry

Engines with a Single Axis of Symmetry (E-SAS, or SAS engine) are hydraulic power sources that are symmetric along an axis. These are done usually using two straight line mechanisms mirrored. Some examples are shown below.
Hydraulic Engines with Two Axes of Symmetry

Engines with a Double Axis of Symmetry (E-DAS, or DAS engine) are hydraulic power sources that are symmetric along two axes. These are done by disconnecting the hydraulic from any anchor points and making it contract from both ends by equal amounts.
As the hydraulic is being centered in these engines, they can be also considered centered oscillating hydraulic engines.
Oscillating Hydraulic Engines (OHE) are the generalized group of engines where the hydraulic changes between two positions. The simplest are the
, though this category primarily focuses on the behavior of the hydraulics themselves, rather than its output.
The following contain hydraulics whose behavior are more dynamic than the previous hydraulic engines shown.
An engine whose hydraulic which moves around its center while it is active is a Centered Oscillating Hydraulic Engine (Centered OHE).
Cycling Hydraulic Engines (CHE) are an extension to
OHE’s have a hydraulic that oscillates between two positions.
CHE’s, however, allow for the hydraulic to move along longer paths—over a series of hydraulic phases—which eventually allow it to return to the beginning.
CHE’s can often take more than two phases before completely returning to their original spots.

The heptagon is the regular polygon with the fewest sides that cannot be perfectly constructed given the tools we have available, however there are some methods for approximation.
Place a 2 meter long segment (We will use blue.)
Copy the blue segment, and paste it after rotating 60 degrees. (We will use green.)
Bisect the blue segment to get its midpoint.
Connect the midpoint of the blue segment to the end of the green segment. (We will use magenta.)
Remove the blue and green segments, as they are no longer needed.
Place two roads such that they form a triangle with the magenta segment.
Turn off the grid (G), and pull the triangle taut such that both roads are as long as they can be. (Shift + Left Click)
The roads will be the spokes used to create the heptagon, and the magenta segment is the side length.

To start constructing the heptagon, copy the triangle and paste it onto a grid point. (I have used an anchor as an example.) Re-enabled the grid (G), and place a 2 meter segment straight up from the anchor point.
Copy the triangle, and rotate it 51 degrees. Make sure the joints circled in white are lined up exactly before pasting.
Rotate the same triangle 103 degrees. Make sure the joints circled in white are lined up exactly before pasting.
Copy the whole shape, flip, and paste.
